🏗️ Section 3 Design: “Common Planning & Delivery Pitfalls”

Role & Position in the Manual
	•	This is a diagnostic section — it surfaces the known failure modes and traps in enterprise delivery.
	•	It acts as a reference map: later chapters provide defenses; this chapter gives names to the dangers.
	•	It helps the reader sense danger early, by recognizing symptom patterns (smells) before escalation.
	•	It also primes the coaching voice: you’ll refer back to this when saying, “This advice is to avoid Pitfall X.”

⸻

🎯 Promise of the Content

By the end of Section 3, the reader will:
	•	Know a catalog of major pitfalls that commonly derail enterprise software projects.
	•	Be able to recognize early warning signs (“smells”) in their own program.
	•	Understand the underlying system pressures that cause these pitfalls (not just surface symptoms).
	•	Have a first-cut response framework — steps to handle a pitfall once spotted.
	•	Appreciate that these are real, political, technical, and process risks — not academic abstractions.
	•	Be mentally prepared to use later sections (requirements, debt, governance) as active countermeasures.

