🧭 Guidance to the Reader: How to Handle Pitfalls

When you detect a symptom or smell of a pitfall, don’t wait. Use the following mitigation sequence:
	1.	Name It Early
	•	Use the recognized label (e.g. “This looks like scope creep”).
	•	Naming surfaces a shared frame and reduces defensiveness.
	2.	Probe the Root Driver
	•	Ask: Why now?
	•	Is it driven by business urgency, a gap in requirements, stakeholder rework, or hidden constraint?
	3.	Quantify the Delta / Impact
	•	Estimate what changes: effort, risk, dependencies.
	•	Translate to cost, schedule, or quality metric.
	•	Use risk buffer logic if necessary.
	4.	Offer Mitigating Trade-Offs
	•	Propose options (scope trim, defer, incremental version, budget supplement).
	•	Lay out what is lost vs gained.
	5.	Document the Decision & Flag Trade-off
	•	Record in Decision Log: “Chose to accept partial scope change — trade-off documentation.”
	•	If quality or architecture is compromised, classify as Expediency Debt with planned remediation.
	6.	Escalate Proportionally
	•	If magnitude exceeds a threshold, bring it to Risk Council or Steering.
	•	Use dashboards to visualize the deviation.
	•	Ensure alignment rather than surprise.
	7.	Embed in Retrospective / Learning
	•	Review the event: what cues were missed, how the mitigation worked, how to prevent in future.
	•	Update guardrails, dashboards, or rituals accordingly.

Pro Tip: Integrate a “pitfall scan” checklist into your planning rituals. Ask before each sprint: Which pitfall(s) might we drift toward this time?

